questions.question:
Trace the output of the following Java code and count the number of String objects created:

String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
String s3 = new String("Hello");
String s4 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(s1 == s2);
System.out.println(s1 == s3);
System.out.println(s3 == s4);
System.out.println(s1.equals(s3));

Consider the following code snippet:

String result = "";
for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
 result = result + i;
}
System.out.println(result);

How many String objects are created? Also, explain how this can be optimized using StringBuilder.

What will be the output of the following code? Also identify any runtime exceptions that may occur:

String s1 = "university";
String s2 = new String("university");
String s3 = "university";
String s4 = s2.intern();

System.out.println(s1 == s2);
System.out.println(s1 == s3);
System.out.println(s1 == s4);
System.out.println(s2 == s4);

Given the following Java code, trace the output step by step:

String a = "Java";
String b = "Java";
String c = new String("Java");
c = c.concat(" Programming");
String d = "Java Programming";

System.out.println(a == b);
System.out.println(a == c);
System.out.println(a == d);
System.out.println(c == d);
System.out.println(a.equals(d));

What is the output of the following code and why?

String str = null;
System.out.println("Hello " + str);
System.out.println(str + 10);
